<paragraph id="8BB58B04FFA1754BFCE4F960FF6F8701" blockId="13.[829,1444,1664,1900]" lastBlockId="14.[144,759,199,985]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA17548FCE4F960FC7B80A6" box="[854,966,1725,1746]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Anterior ventral process on sixth abdominal segment in male much shorter than posterior process; ventral process on telson of medium size; outer spine of uropodal exopod nearly reaching distal end of exopod in male but is much shorter in females (by far nor reaching distal end of exopod). Petasma: sheath without hook, subconical, with distal longitudinal rows of fine scales, plate-like structures small, with entire margins; processus long, needle-like, finely setose along medial part, without a dense brush of long terminal setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB58B04FFA2754BFF1AFEA3FD57841D" blockId="14.[144,759,199,985]" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFF1AFEA3FEB187E7" box="[168,268,382,403]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Remarks</emphasis>
: The outer tooth of the uropodal exopod, which is far from reaching (nearly reaching in the other 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFF6BFE66FEE687A5" box="[217,347,443,465]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Luciferidae</taxonomicName>
) the distal end of exopod, distinguishes females of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFEC0FE07FE51879B" authorityName="Borridaile" authorityYear="1916" box="[370,492,474,495]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hanseni">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFEC0FE07FE51879B" box="[370,492,474,495]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. hanseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other species of the genus and family. The processus ventralis is very similar to that in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFE18FDCAFDAF8458" authorityName="Vereshchaka &amp; Olesen &amp; Lunina" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Borradaile" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[426,530,535,556]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="faxoni">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFE18FDCAFDAF8458" box="[426,530,535,556]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. faxoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFDE7FDCAFD008458" authorityName="Vereshchaka &amp; Olesen &amp; Lunina" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Bowman &amp; McCain" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[597,701,535,556]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFDE7FDCAFD008458" box="[597,701,535,556]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in the position of the fine lateral setae (medial in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFF1DFD89FE94841D" authorityName="Borridaile" authorityYear="1916" box="[175,297,596,617]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hanseni">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFF1DFD89FE94841D" box="[175,297,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. hanseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and apical in 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFE62FD89FD8A841D" authorityName="Vereshchaka &amp; Olesen &amp; Lunina" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Borradaile" baseAuthorityYear="1915" box="[464,567,596,617]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="faxoni">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFE62FD89FD8A841D" box="[464,567,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. faxoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C0AF087FFA2754BFDC0FD89FD67841D" authorityName="Vereshchaka &amp; Olesen &amp; Lunina" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Bowman &amp; McCain" baseAuthorityYear="1967" box="[626,730,596,617]" class="Malacostraca" family="Luciferidae" genus="Belzebub" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFDC0FD89FD67841D" box="[626,730,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">B. chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB58B04FFA2754BFF1AFDAFFE3C84D3" blockId="14.[144,759,199,985]" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFF1AFDAFFEA284F3" box="[168,287,626,647]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Etymology</emphasis>
: Named after Dr Hans J. H. Hansen, a Danish carcinologist.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB58B04FFA2754BFF1AFD72FF6B85AD" blockId="14.[144,759,199,985]" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFF1AFD72FD9D84B1" box="[168,544,687,709]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">
Geographical distribution (
<figureCitation id="13319781FFA2754BFE46FD6DFD9D84B1" box="[500,544,688,709]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="13.[166,245,673,692]" captionTargetBox="[393,1221,198,639]" captionTargetId="figure-492@13.[393,1221,198,639]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 12. Provisory macroscale geographical distribution of species of Lucifer and Belzebub. Based upon Dana Expedition data, Hansen (1919), Bowman &amp; McCain (1967), Omori (1977), Lee et al. (1992), Perez-Farfante &amp; Kensley (1997), Antony (2005), Ma, Xu &amp; Zhou (2009), Xu (2010), and Teodoro et al. (2012)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5460859" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5460859/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Fig.</figureCitation>
</emphasis>
12
<emphasis id="B97E5716FFA2754BFDF6FD6DFDEE84B1" box="[580,595,688,709]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">):</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFDD7FD72FD4F84B1" box="[613,754,687,709]" name="Madagascar" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
; Red Sea; around 
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFECAFD13FE0A8490" box="[376,439,718,740]" name="India" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">India</collectingCountry>
; South 
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFD94FD13FDD68490" box="[550,619,718,740]" name="China" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">China</collectingCountry>
Sea, East 
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFF22FD30FF688577" box="[144,213,749,771]" name="China" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">China</collectingCountry>
Sea; Changjiang estuary; 
<collectingRegion id="49CE45E6FFA2754BFDA5FD30FDC98577" box="[535,628,749,771]" country="Australia" name="Victoria" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Victoria</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFD36FD30FD4F8577" box="[644,754,749,771]" name="Australia" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Australia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49CE45E6FFA2754BFF22FCD6FEB98555" box="[144,260,779,801]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
, South Pacific Ocean. This species has been recently reported from the Mediterranean coast of 
<collectingCountry id="F31DCB94FFA2754BFF44FC95FE87852A" box="[246,314,840,862]" name="Israel" pageId="14" pageNumber="29">Israel</collectingCountry>
, which probably has resulted from a recent invasion through the Suez Canal, rather than the species having gone undetected in the intervening period (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9BF6F5FFA2754BFE21FC79FF7785AD" author="De Grave S &amp; Einav R &amp; Galil BS" pageId="14" pageNumber="29" pagination="115 - 118" refId="ref9294" refString="De Grave S, Einav R, Galil BS. 2012. Recent records of the Indo-Pacific species, Lucifer hanseni Nobili, 1905 (Crustacea; Decapoda; Luciferidae) from the Mediterranean coast of Israel. BioInvasions Records 1: 115 - 118." type="journal article" year="2012">De Grave, Einav &amp; Galil, 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
